Lithium-ion batteries (LIBs) are essential for portable electronics and electric vehicles due to their relatively high energy/power density, reasonable cycle life, and cost-effectiveness. As the demand for LIBs continues to rise, extensive research efforts have been devoted to enhancing their performance. Graphite is a well-established anode material, recognised for its favourable (de)lithiation reversibility and cycle life, however it is limited by its relatively low theoretical capacity (372 mAh/g) [1]. In contrast, silicon has a significantly higher theoretical capacity (3579 mAh/g for Li15Si



                              4


                     ) [2], yet its practical utilisation is hindered by challenges, such as: substantial volume change, voltage hysteresis, non-linear multi-phase behaviours and particle cracking/pulverisation [3]. To overcome these limitations, composite silicon/graphite electrodes have been proposed, with several commercial applications already reported [4–6].

On the discrepancy between the model predictions and experimental data for graphite active material loss (LAM
G r
), this may be because of the simplified LAM model used, more complex fracture behaviour, non-linearly varying material properties or varying behaviour of SEI growth on freshly cracked vs existing surfaces. Furthermore, Paris’ law is used to describe the fatigue crack growth in the electrode particles due to its versatility and simplicity. However, Paris’ law is generally applicable to the mid-stages of crack growth as opposed to crack initiation or rapid failure, and in combination with the complex stress profiles in real battery particles may explain observed variations in these regions. Furthermore, parameters such as the Paris’ law exponential term (
